{"query": "What are the general outcomes of introducing different types of peatland vegetationsuch as whole plants versus fragments or seedsto aid restoration?", "summary": "Different methods of introducing vegetation to peatlands show varying levels of success. When introducing seeds, studies show mixed results: some planted herb seeds successfully germinated, with wetland-characteristic plants colonizing sown plots, while other studies found no increase in plant species richness or herb cover compared to unsown plots. For shrub/tree seeds, germination occurred but survival was often poor, with all germinated willow seedlings dying within one month in one study.

Using whole plants or fragments appears more successful than seeds. Adding moss fragments (especially Sphagnum) to peatland surfaces resulted in moss cover ranging from negligible to over 90% in multiple studies, with sown plots typically having higher cover than unsown plots. Adding mixed vegetation containing Sphagnum also proved effective, with Sphagnum cover ranging from less than 1% to 73% in sown plots. The moss layer transfer technique, which spreads whole moss layers, was particularly successful with restored areas developing bog-characteristic plant communities within 11 years and achieving greater vegetation cover than unrestored areas.

However, success rates vary significantly depending on environmental conditions and additional interventions, with some studies reporting very low survival or cover unless plots were mulched, shaded, or received other treatments.", "action_ids": ["1823", "1824", "3260", "1821", "1822", "1804"]}

